  ## 8\. Case studies
  
  Case studies look at real-life experiments or businesses that have succeeded in using certain tactics or strategies. They’re effective because readers are more inclined to buy into information when it’s backed by proof.
  
  In [this case study](https://ahrefs.com/blog/wise-seo-case-study/) of fintech company [Wise](https://wise.com/), we explored five reasons why its SEO strategy is so admirable:
  
  ![Except of an Ahrefs case study type of blog article showing five reasons why Wise's SEO strategy is good.](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201211%20388%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  We also weaved in our product—the Ahrefs toolset—where we could.
  
  ![Excerpt of an Ahrefs article talking about content optimization for featured snippets](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201339%201326%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  For your case study to be effective, it has to give the reader some “wins”—clear takeaways that they can apply to their business. Ideally, you should feature a business that’s either well known or has a unique enough selling proposition to entice readers to click on the blog post.
  
  ### Best practices
  
  - Give readers some clear takeaways (e.g., Oatly SEO Case Study: 5 Lessons You Can Learn From the Oat Drink Giant and Its IPO) so they’re more likely to read your blog post
  
  More Examples
  
  - [Link Building Case Study: How We Built Backlinks With a ‘Stats’ Page (And Ranked #1)](https://ahrefs.com/blog/link-building-case-study/)
  
  ## 9\. Cheat sheets and checklists
  
  Cheat sheets and checklists are essentially the same type of blog post format and may include a clear breakdown of the steps required to reach a goal.
  
  Unlike how-to guides, which may sometimes be ambiguous in explaining how something works, checklists and cheat sheets are effective because they tell you **exactly** what you need to achieve something.
  
  Here’s a [concise SEO checklist](https://ahrefs.com/blog/seo-checklist/) we crafted for a blog post. We later repurposed the checklist [as a tweet](https://twitter.com/ahrefs/status/1426963210528247822):
  
  Twitter Embed
  
  > Looking for a complete SEO checklist for 2021?
  >
  > Here’s one you can follow. [pic.twitter.com/65brjXPBcg](https://t.co/65brjXPBcg)
  >
  > — Ahrefs (@ahrefs) [August 15, 2021](https://twitter.com/ahrefs/status/1426963210528247822?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
  
  In the above blog post, we shared that our SEO checklist helped grow our blog to over 640,000 monthly search visits. Then we shared that same checklist with users before going into a breakdown of each of the elements in the cheat sheet.
  
  ### Best practices
  
  - Arrange your checklists/cheat sheets in chronological order so that the reader knows exactly how to reach a goal
  
  More Examples
  
  - [How to Do a Content Audit in 2022](https://ahrefs.com/blog/content-audit/)
  
  ## 10\. Templates
  
  Similar to what the name suggests, template blog posts include templates on how to achieve something—as in the case of [this blog post](https://ahrefs.com/blog/marketing-plan/) on how to create a one-page marketing plan.
  
  We recommend using this format:
  
  - What is \[topic\]?
  - Why is \[topic\] important?
  - How can I make \[topic\] work for me?
  - Template
  
  You can share your template at the start of the article, which is what we normally do, or at the bottom of the blog post.
  
  ![Excerpt of an Ahrefs template type of blog post about a one-page marketing plan.](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201123%201076%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  There are also multiple ways to let readers access your template in these types of blog posts: We usually offer them as a free, copyable template (via Google Docs), but you may decide to create a downloadable template instead.
  
  ### Best practices
  
  - Keep your template simple and organized, with guiding questions or tips for open-ended fields
  
  ![Example of a simple and organized template](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20210%20140%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  More Examples
  
  - [How to Write a Press Release](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-write-a-press-release/)
  - [Steal Our SEO Report Template (Inspired by SEO Experts)](https://ahrefs.com/blog/seo-report-template/)
  
  ## Final thoughts
  
  These types of blog formats are not the be-all and end-all when it comes to writing a good blog post.
  
  Try to mix things up depending on what you think works best. For instance, this guide to [creating SEO-friendly URLs](https://ahrefs.com/blog/seo-friendly-urls/) starts with a step-by-step guide, then looks at some best practices in a listicle format.
  
  It’s all about experimenting and figuring out what your readers want, so don’t limit yourself.
  
  Have questions or comments? I’d love to hear them [on Twitter](https://twitter.com/RebLiew).
  
