  Contents
  
  - [Get to the point, don't waffle](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#get-to-the-point "Get to the point, don't waffle")
  - [Make it scannable](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#make-it-scannable "Make it scannable")
  - [Format for the dominant content type](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#format-for-dominant-content-type "Format for the dominant content type")
  - [Formatting specifics](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#formatting-specifics "Formatting specifics")
  
  When you’re writing a blog post, it’s easy to overlook the formatting. But how _exactly_ should you format your blog posts to get more engagement and search success?
  
  Contents
  
  - [Get to the point, don't waffle](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#get-to-the-point "Get to the point, don't waffle")
  - [Make it scannable](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#make-it-scannable "Make it scannable")
  - [Format for the dominant content type](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#format-for-dominant-content-type "Format for the dominant content type")
  - [Formatting specifics](https://ahrefs.com/blog/how-to-format-a-blog-post/#formatting-specifics "Formatting specifics")
  
  ## Get to the point, don’t waffle
  
  When it comes to writing the introduction, keep it simple, concise, and tailored to your audience.
  
  If you want a defined approach for formatting your introduction, you can use the Problem-Solution-Proof (PSP) introduction formula.
  ![Problem-Solution-Proof intro formula, via Ahrefs Blog ](https://ahrefs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/image15-6.png)
  Using the PSP formula means you can get straight to the core of the topic by outlining the problem, giving a solution, and providing proof of why your audience should trust you—all in just two paragraphs.
  
  It also means there’s space to put an image above the fold, making your post more visually engaging for visitors.
  
  ## Make it scannable
  
  Once you’ve perfected your introduction, it’s time to consider how to arrange the rest of the article.
  
  The reality is that many people do not read from start to finish anymore. A study by [Nielson](https://www.nngroup.com/articles/how-users-read-on-the-web/) suggested that only 16% of its test users read an article word by word.
  
  So it’s important to make your articles scannable to maximize engagement on your blog. The easiest way to do this is to use headings or, more specifically, [H1 tags](https://ahrefs.com/blog/h1-tag/) and other <H> tags.
  
  Headings also have a secondary benefit, as they help to provide an SEO-friendly structure for your article.
  
  Here’s what it looks like in practice. You want to aim for a clear hierarchy.
  ![Illustration of how headings create hierarchy and improve user experience, via Ahrefs Blog](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201495%201600%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  In my opinion, your headings should have two qualities:
  
  - **Individually,** they should have an impact and catch the reader’s attention.
  - **Collectively,** they need to form a logical outline and indicate the key elements of the article at a glance.
  
  In practice, it’s often a balancing act: You’ll need to be able to structure posts in a logical, hierarchical way and also entice the reader to read on.
  
  ## Format for the dominant content type
  
  Generally speaking, a lot of content on the internet falls into these categories:
  
  - List posts
  - Step-by-step guides
  - Beginner’s guides
  - Expanded definition
  - Reviews
  
  For this reason, before you create your written content, it’s a good idea to research what type of content is already ranking for your target keywords so that you can format it properly.
  
  This may seem like overkill, but you don’t want to waste time creating content in a format that readers are unlikely to engage with. So it pays to get it right from the start.
  
  For example, if we write a 2,000-word article on “how to tie a tie” and visitors are expecting a video, it’s unlikely our written content will ever get a chance to appear at the top of the SERP because it’s not the type of content our audience is looking for.
  
  To show you how quick it is to check for the dominant content type, let’s jump into Ahrefs’ [Keywords Explorer](https://ahrefs.com/keywords-explorer), plug in “how to tie a tie,” and scroll down to the **SERP overview.**
  ![SERP overview for "how to tie a tie," via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20848%20332%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  We can see from this search that the top result is a video hosted on YouTube. That means in order to compete in this SERP, we’ll probably need to create a video on this topic.
  
  With that said, let’s take a look at some of the most common written content types that you can easily format for.
  
  ### List posts
  
  List posts are very common, especially in certain niches where visitors are looking for inspiration or ideas.
  
  Let’s start by plugging in “things to do in capri” in [Keywords Explorer](https://ahrefs.com/keywords-explorer).
  
  If we scroll down to the **SERP overview,** we can see that almost all of the results contain a number, meaning they are likely to be list posts.
  ![SERP overview for "things to do in capri," via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201204%201350%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  From this example, as there are so many list posts ranking on the first page for this query, we’ll need to stick to the list post format in order to stand a chance of ranking on this SERP.
  
  Here’s an example of the format you can use for a list post:
  ![Format of a list post, via Ahrefs Blog ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20900%201587%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  ### Step-by-step guides
  
  Let’s now plug in another different keyword. I’ve added “podcasting guide” into [Keywords Explorer](https://ahrefs.com/keywords-explorer) to see what we get.
  ![SERP overview for "podcasting guide," via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201118%20606%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  Although the SERP result titles contain numbers as well, we can see that the dominant content type at the top of the SERP is about providing step-by-step guides.
  
  Tip
  
  Sometimes, you’ll need to click on the URLs and visit the webpage to double-check the content type.
  
  Here’s an example of the format you can use for a step-by-step guide:
  ![Format for a step-by-step guide, via Ahrefs Blog ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20830%201600%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  ### Beginner’s guides
  
  Let’s take a look at another content type. I’ve plugged the keyword “chess basics” into the **SERP overview.**
  ![SERP overview for "chess basics," via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201164%201232%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  From my highlights, we can see that the title tags of these pages are aimed at beginners.
  
  If we wanted to create a beginner’s guide for a topic, the format of the post might look something like this:
  ![Format for a beginner's guide, via Ahrefs Blog ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20900%201539%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  ### Expanded definition
  
  Another common type of content is the expanded definition. This type of content explains the meaning of a thing or concept before going into more detail about it.
  
  Let’s plug in “latte” into [Keywords Explorer](https://ahrefs.com/keywords-explorer) and scroll down to the **SERP overview.**
  ![SERP overview for "latte," via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20976%20324%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  In this example, we can see that the top result is asking what a latte is.
  
  We can use this format to build out a post on this topic.
  ![Format for "expanded definition" post, via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20900%201851%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  Another element you can add to an “expanded definition” format post is [FAQs](https://ahrefs.com/blog/faq-pages-seo/). Adding this section with [schema](https://ahrefs.com/blog/schema-markup/) can be a good combination.
  
  Here’s an example of some popular FAQs about H1 tags from our blog:
  ![FAQs example, via Ahrefs Blog ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201330%201012%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  ### Reviews
  
  One of the most popular content formats is the review format. This format is fairly self-explanatory—visitors to your site are expecting the product or service to be reviewed.
  
  Let’s take a look at a “review” SERP in [Keywords Explorer](https://ahrefs.com/keywords-explorer).
  ![SERP overview for "airpods max review," via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201486%201168%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  This is one of the easier-to-spot formats, and you can see almost every SERP result title has the word “review” in it.
  
  When it comes to writing reviews, Google provides detailed guidance on how to write a good review, which you can read about below.
  
  Further reading
  
  - [Write High Quality Reviews](https://developers.google.com/search/docs/specialty/ecommerce/write-high-quality-reviews)
  
  ## Formatting specifics
  
  Many content creators know how to format content. But in the rush to produce content, it’s easy to let the quality of the formatting slide or omit it altogether.
  
  Here’s a reminder of what you should and shouldn’t do:
  
  ### Don’t make your article needlessly long—keep it succinct and to the point
  
  If you are writing to reach a word count, then you are creating content wrong. You should really focus on writing the best blog post you can.
  
  Though, it’s useful to know how long different pages on the SERP are because it gives you a sense of the opportunity available.
  
  The best way to check is to use [Keywords Explorer’s](https://ahrefs.com/keywords-explorer) **SERP overview,** as it lists the word count of the top pages on the SERP.
  ![Word count of results on a SERP for "what is a latte," via Ahrefs' Keywords Explorer ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201086%201240%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  Using a tool like this, we can see that for this topic, the number #1 ranking article is the shortest article on the SERP.
  
  So if we [hired a freelance writer](https://ahrefs.com/blog/hiring-freelance-writers/) to write a 4000-word blog post on “what is a latte,” chances are, it would be too much.
  
  ### Use text formatting for emphasis
  
  Basic text formatting, like using bold, italic, or <a> links, is a good way to highlight certain parts of your content for search engines.
  
  Google’s John Muller had this to say about bolding text:
  
  > Does bolding important points on a paragraph help the SEO? Yes it does. It does help us to better understand that paragraph or that page.
  >
  > ![John Mueller](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20210%20140%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  >
  > John Mueller,Search Advocate [Google](https://www.google.com/)
  
  ### Use a table of contents
  
  ![Table of content example, via Ahrefs Blog ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%20387%20747%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  I mentioned making your blog posts scannable earlier on. In my opinion, there is no better way to do this than by adding a table of contents, as it summarizes your content in a few lines that users can click.
  
  Adding a table of contents is a good way to allow your page’s visitors to scan your content’s core topics quickly.
  
  It can also trigger [sitelinks](https://ahrefs.com/blog/sitelinks/), which can potentially help you win even more organic clicks.
  
  Tip
  
  If you use WordPress, you can use a free plugin like [Easy Table of Contents](https://wordpress.org/plugins/easy-table-of-contents/) to add a table of contents to your blog posts automatically.
  
  ### Use internal linking to explain other concepts
  
  [Internal linking for SEO](https://ahrefs.com/blog/internal-links-for-seo/) is one of the most powerful aspects of formatting a blog post, in my opinion.
  
  Check out our video and guides on how to do it below.
  
  Further reading
  
  - [What Are Internal Links?](https://ahrefs.com/seo/glossary/internal-link)
  - [Internal Links for SEO: An Actionable Guide](https://ahrefs.com/blog/internal-links-for-seo/)
  
  ### Use external links when linking to useful resources
  
  External links should be used more sparingly than internal links. But it’s good to link to relevant, trusted sources that help provide context for your content.
  
  ### Add an author bio
  
  Adding an author bio is a good way to provide legitimacy for your readers. If visitors to your site can see that the content is written by a real person, it adds to its authenticity.
  ![Josh Hardwick's author bio on the Ahrefs Blog ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201200%20648%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  At Ahrefs, we have an author bio below every post with links to our social media profiles.
  
  ### Use images to enhance your content
  
  Generally speaking, it’s a good idea to add images to help convey more meaning to your content.
  
  It’s important because some SERPs will pull through images from your articles.
  
  Here’s an example where images from my blog post on [website structure](https://ahrefs.com/blog/website-structure/) were pulled into the Google SERP:
  ![Images pulled from an Ahrefs article on Google's SERP ](data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%22http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%22%20viewBox=%220%200%201108%20430%22%3E%3C/svg%3E)
  
  #### Use original, web-ready images
  
  When it comes to images, it’s easy to use a stock image. But a better idea is to use your own original images where possible. They also should ideally be “web ready.” This means using [WEBP](https://developers.google.com/speed/webp) image formats for the best performance.
  
  When it comes to optimizing your images, you can also use [alt text](https://ahrefs.com/blog/alt-text/) as part of your basic [image optimization](https://ahrefs.com/blog/image-seo/).
  
  ## Final thoughts
  
  Many of the elements of formatting a blog post for search are not difficult. Yet surprisingly, many online publishers still don’t take the time to do it.
  
  Taking a structured approach to formatting can help your content stand out from the crowd and get it recognized on the SERPs.
  
  Got more questions? Ping me [on Twitter](https://twitter.com/chris_at_b449). 🙂
  
